    Amplifier -> Filter;
    Filter -> OutputStage;
    OutputStage -> Multimeter;
}
```

```Explanations
Sensor: The NTC thermistor is the primary temperature sensing element. Its resistance decreases with increasing temperature. The NTCLE100E3 will change resistance with temperature, providing the variable input to the system.

Linearization: A linearization resistor is connected in parallel with the thermistor to create a more linear response over the desired temperature range. The specific value is chosen based on the characteristic curve of the NTCLE100E3 to linearize the response around the midpoint of the temperature range.

Excitation: A constant current source is used to bias the thermistor. By keeping the current constant, the voltage across the thermistor will be directly proportional to its resistance, which changes with temperature. This also helps in minimizing self-heating effects, as the power dissipation can be controlled by setting an appropriate current level.

Amplifier: An instrumentation amplifier is used to amplify the small voltage change across the thermistor. It is designed to have high input impedance to avoid loading the thermistor circuit and to provide precise gain to map the thermistor voltage range to the desired 0-20V output range.

Filter: A low-pass filter is included to remove any high-frequency noise that could interfere with the accurate temperature measurement. This also acts as an anti-aliasing filter to ensure that the multimeter's ADC receives a clean signal.

OutputStage: The voltage output stage converts the amplified and filtered signal into a voltage range suitable for measurement by the multimeter. It scales the voltage to the 0-20V range and ensures that the output impedance is low enough to drive the multimeter without causing measurement errors.

Multimeter: This represents the multimeter's internal ADC, which is external to the analog signal conditioning circuit. It converts the analog voltage signal into a digital value that can be read on the multimeter display. The characteristics of this ADC influence the final design of the analog front-end to ensure compatibility and accurate readings.
```

